AU  - Bursztyn, Leonardo
AU  - Ferman, Bruno
AU  - Fiorin, Stefano
AU  - Kanz, Martin
AU  - Rao, Gautam
T1  - Status Goods: Experimental Evidence from Platinum Credit Cards*
PY  - 2018
Y1  - 2018/08/01
DO  - 10.1093/qje/qjx048
JO  - The Quarterly Journal of Economics
JA  - Q J Econ
VL  - 133
IS  - 3
SP  - 1561
EP  - 1595
SN  - 0033-5533
AB  - This article provides field-experimental evidence on status goods. We work with an Indonesian bank that markets platinum credit cards to high-income customers. In a first experiment, we show that demand for the platinum card exceeds demand for a nondescript control product with identical benefits, suggesting demand for the pure status aspect of the card. Transaction data reveal that platinum cards are more likely to be used in social contexts, implying social image motivations. In a second experiment, we provide evidence of positional externalities from the consumption of these status goods. A final experiment provides suggestive evidence that increasing self-esteem causally reduces demand for status goods, indicating that social image might be a substitute for self-image.
Y2  - 3/25/2024
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/qje/qjx048
ER  - 



